\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li1122\ri859\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin859\lin1122\itap0\pararsid4539373 {\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 "Weights and measures may be ranked among }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 
the necessaries of life to every }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 individual of human society. They enter into the economical arrangements}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
and daily concerns of every family. They are necessary to every occupation of}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 human industry; to the distribution and security of every species of property;}{
\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 to every transaction of trade and commerce; to the labors of the husbandman;}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 to}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 
 the ingenuity of the artificer;}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  to }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 the studies of the philosopher;}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  to the}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{
\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 resea}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 rches of the antiquarian;}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  to the navigation of the mariner, and the}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  marches of the soldier;}{
\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  to all the exchanges of peace, and all the operations of}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 war. The knowledge of them, as in established use, is among the first}{
\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 elements of education, and is often learned by those who learn nothing else,}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
not even to read and write. This knowledge is riveted in the memory by the}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373  }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 habitual application of it to the employments of men throughout life. "}{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li1122\ri859\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin859\lin1122\itap0\pararsid4539373 {\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373\charrsid4539373 }{\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid4539373 {\i\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 JOHN QUINCY ADAMS - Report to the Congress, 1821
\par }\pard \s15\qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid4539373 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4539373 
\par }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Weights and measures were among the earliest tools invented by man. Primitive societies}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
needed rudimentary measures for many tasks: constructing dwellings of an appropriate size and}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 shape, fashioning clothing and bartering food or raw materials.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 

\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Man understandably turned first to parts of his body and his natural surroundings for measuring}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 instruments. Early Babylonian and Egyptian records, and the Bible, indicate that length was }{\f1\fs22\insrsid10689432\charrsid4539373 first}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 measured with the forearm, hand, or }{\f1\fs22\insrsid10689432 finger}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  and that time was measured by the periods of the sun,}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 moon, and other heavenly bodies. When it was necessary to compare the capacities of containers}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
such as gourds or clay or metal vessels, they were filled with plant seeds that were then counted}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 to measure the volumes. With the development of scales as a means for weighing, seeds and
}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 stones served as standards. For instance, the "carat," still used as a mass unit for gems, is derived}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
from the carob seed.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par As societies evolved, measurements became more complex. The invention of numbering}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 systems and the science of mathematics made it possible to create whole systems of measurement}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 units suited to trade and commerce, land division, taxation, and scientific research. For these}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
more sophisticated uses, it was necessary not only to weigh and measure more complex things -}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
it was also necessary to do it accurately time after time and in different places. However, with}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
limited international exchange of goods and communication of ideas, it is not surprising that}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 different systems for the sam
e purpose developed and became established in different parts of the}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 world - even in different parts of the same country.
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 THE ENGLISH SYSTEM}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 The measurement system commonly used in the United States today is nearly the same as that}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 brought by the colonists from England. These measures had their origins in a variety of cultures-Babylonian, Egyptian, Roman, Anglo-Saxon, and Norman French. The ancient "digit," "palm,"}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 "span" and "cubic" units of length slowly lost preference to the length units "inch," "foot," and}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 "yard."}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Roman contributions include the use of 12 as a base number (the foot is divided into 12 inches)}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 and the words from which we derive many of our present measurement unit names. For example,}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
the 12 divisions of the Roman "pes," or foot were called unciae. Our words "inch" and "ounce"}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 are both derived from that Latin word.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 The "yard" as a measure of length can be traced back to early Saxon kings. They wore a sash or}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 girdle around the waist that could be removed and used as a convenient measuring device. The}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
word "yard" comes from the Saxon word "gird" meaning the circumference of}{\f1\fs22\insrsid6506645  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 a person's waist.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  
\par 
\par }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Standardizing various units and combining them into loosely related systems of measurement}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 units sometimes occurred in fascinating ways
. Tradition holds that King Henry I decreed that a}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 yard should be the distance from the tip of his nose to the end of his outstretched thumb. The}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 length of a furlong (or furrow-long) was established by early Tudor rulers as 220 yards. This led}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Queen Eli
zabeth I to declare in the 16th century, that henceforth the traditional Roman mile of}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 5000 feet would be replaced by one of 5280 feet, making the mile exactly eight furlongs and}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 providing a convenient relationship between the furlong and the mile.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 Thus, through royal edicts, England by the 18th century had achieved a greater degree of}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 standardization than other European countries. The English units were well suited to commerce}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
and trade because they had been developed and refilled to meet commercial needs. Through}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 English colonization and its dominance of world commerce during the 17th, 18th, and 19th}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 centuries, the English system of measurement units became established in many parts of the}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
world, including the American colonies.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par However, standards still differed to an extent undesirable for commerce, even among the 13
\par American colonies. The need for greater uniformity led to clauses in the Articles of
\par Confederation (ratified by the original colonies in 1781) and the Constitution of the United States
\par (ratified in 1790) that gave Congress the power to }{\f1\fs22\insrsid6506645 fix}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  uniform standards for weights and
\par measures. Today, standards supplied to all the states by the National Institute of Standards and
\par Technology assure uniformity throughout the country.
\par 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 THE METRIC SYSTEM}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 The need for a single worldwide coordinated measurement system was recognized over 300 years}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 ago. Gabriel Mouton, Vicar of St. Paul's Church in Lyons and an astronomer, proposed in 1670 a}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
comprehensive decimal measurement system based on the length of one minute of arc of a great}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 circle of the Earth. Mouton also proposed the swing length of a pendulum with a frequency of}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 one beat per second as the unit of length. A pendulum with this beat would have been fairly}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 easily reproducible, thus
 facilitating the widespread distribution of uniform standards. Other}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 proposals were made, but more than a century elapsed before any action was taken.}{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 In 1790, in the midst of the French Revolution, the National Assembly of France requested the}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 French Academy of Sciences to "deduce an invariable standard for all the measures and all the}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 weights."}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201\charrsid4539373 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
\par }\pard \s15\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid12808722 {\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 The Commission appointed by the Academy created a system that was, at once, simple and}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201 
 }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 scientific. The unit of length was to be a portion of the Earth's circumference. Measures for}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 
capacity (volume) and mass were to be derived from the unit of length, thus relating the basic}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 units of the system to each o}{\f1\fs22\insrsid6506645 ther and to nature. Furthermore,}{
\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373  larger and smaller multiples of each}{\f1\fs22\insrsid1399201  }{\f1\fs22\insrsid4522937\charrsid4539373 unit were to be created by multiplying or dividing the basic units by 10 and its powers. This}{
